  <h3>Specialty Retailers</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>**Natural wine shops** often have the best selection</li>
    <li>**Progressive wine bars** sometimes sell bottles</li>
    <li>**Online retailers** like Jenny & François or Ordinaire Wine</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>What to Look For</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Terms like "natural," "low sulfite," or "unfined/unfiltered"</li>
    <li>Organic or biodynamic certifications</li>
    <li>Producers known for minimal intervention</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Storage and Serving</h2>

  <h3>Special Considerations</h3>
  <p>Natural wines can be more delicate than conventional wines:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>**Store in cool, dark conditions**</li>
    <li>**Some may need refrigeration after opening**</li>
    <li>**Can evolve quickly in the glass**</li>
    <li>**May benefit from decanting to blow off any reduction**</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Misconceptions</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>**"Natural wine always tastes funky"** - Many are clean and delicious</li>
    <li>**"All natural wine is orange wine"** - Natural wines come in all styles</li>
    <li>**"Natural means organic"** - Related but not identical concepts</li>
    <li>**"Natural wine has no sulfites"** - Some have naturally occurring sulfites</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Getting Started</h2>

  <h3>Beginner-Friendly Producers</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Start with established natural wine producers</li>
    <li>Try natural wines from familiar grape varieties</li>
    <li>Ask knowledgeable wine shop staff for recommendations</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Developing Your Palate</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Compare natural and conventional wines from the same region</li>
    <li>Attend natural wine tastings</li>
    <li>Keep an open mind about different flavor profiles</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Natural wine offers a unique window into pure grape expression and traditional winemaking methods. While not every bottle will suit every palate, the category rewards exploration and offers discoveries impossible with conventional winemaking.</p>

